The C.S.S.D. in Prague doesn't know Voldemort or the bakery.
The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will have to overcome, it seems, the obvious language barriers so that the members of the Prague City Council and the City Council can understand their new SDG colleagues.
Aktuálně.cz "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the marked slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The codified dictionary that used the flower and cream of Prague politics during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the metropolis' best-known characters, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councillors hardly understand these familiar concepts.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I really don't know".
"I'm rather a novice in Prague politics", said culture councillor Lukáš Kaucký during the terminology exam for "college".
And as for the veteran politician, Karel Březina reacted the same way.
You may be familiar with the concept of a golf hole.
"It's probably the only expression of all the ones you've asked me to use from time to time".
"Otherwise, I don't usually use slang".
From the glossary, whose definitions were published by Aktuálně.cz last June ahead of the ODS voting congress, the editorial staff selected six examples, in particular those that are especially related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
The socialists had to explain the concepts of "Voldemort", "Prague's largest golf hole", "going to the pastry shop", "bull's neck", "treason of the capital" and "armor".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be in charge of education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, refused to do so outright.
"I don't get into this stuff or value how civic democrats have fun".
"What really matters to me is how we will understand each other in the implementation of our programmes", he said.
As we have seen, councilman Lukáš Kaucký would not have realized that the above title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former Bém mayor Roman Janoušek.
The word "Voldemort" means nothing to Kaucký; the only term he got right on the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"It's the Blanka tunnel", says Kaucký, who immediately adds: "But I know it from the news".
"I'm going to have to sign up for a language course", he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the councillor for the Environment Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both social democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachy even knows where to find that character; moreover, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think he means going to a Prague company"; it is soon revealed to Plachy that this is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that he got such knowledge from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the test participants, no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms exists among the social democrats.
"I asked my classmates, but it really doesn't seem like we have anything in common".
"Rather, we use nicknames among ourselves, sometimes abbreviations or word games with names", says Prague's ČSSD president Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call her Hulda.
"At school they called me Bříza, but I don't know if my peers call me that too", confesses Karel Březina, who goes by his own nickname.
Aktuálně.cz tried the name and it works.
For his party colleagues, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they were associated before the election cheats during the party sponsorship, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") by some of his colleagues.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that the Social Democrats tolerate in party speech.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz even discovered other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The Doctor of the rights of the batons" apparently recalls that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law at the Bratislava police academy.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", according to a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, unmarried and childless.
Women who "become" witches are sent to an isolated area, so they don't harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a fate".
"Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help out with chores and have children", explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, works in a special home for more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued a pamphlet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
This has a catch, though.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso are illiterate", warns the newspaper Die Standard of the disadvantages of written awareness-raising.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news came out on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate combination of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman caught on to the oil used for ritual anointings.
She caught fire when the group wanted to "cast out the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Soul-eaters have always been a danger".
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to pacify the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president was still involved.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a widespread witch hunt that allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic".
"To help him, he brought in shamans from neighbouring Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forcibly took men and women chosen at random from Gambian villages to the president's property in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay at the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
The tenant of Bakala: heats himself with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The elderly, shy man walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rental flats in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story lease agreements: his, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving his sentence.
The three of them just got caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the child will pay 4,100 crowns for a two-room apartment with a second-class separate kitchen from next year.
"Moreover, there is no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler", the man points to his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it", he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until 7 December, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But man only makes a nod.
"Each one says something", he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great testing ground for liberalisation.
After New Year's it will happen with the vast majority of the flats which, in the Czech Republic, were until now under a regulated lease.
That is why Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG Mining Waiting Room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a number-taking machine.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out.
He barely has time to read "157" and the number is already displayed on the large screen at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple comes to ask, but the crowd in the hall isn't here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve usual problems, as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters an increase in the rent of between 15 and 38%.
On 18 November a special window opens at the customer service centre for new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting", responds the workers who are in it when the customer introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalisation and the former Bakala miners' flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already being discussed loud and clear by the deputy speaker of the Ostrava-based Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek of the ČSSD, and now they appear continuously in the local newspapers.
"Twenty years later, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change my fucking bathroom dish", ventures the man mentioned in the introduction.
According to the workers, they are mostly retired people who come to see if they get a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the RPG special offer.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before 15 December will also receive half of the discount on the February rent.
However, the window of "liberalisation" of mining certainly fails to dispel the flood of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for rent in 2011", estimates the window attendant.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and in its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the parties cannot reach an agreement on the rent, an independent judge must decide the matter.
"It is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely lawful way forward", warns RPG on its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here", says one of RPG Byty's employees and a man standing in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the right answer.
"I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left over for food; I have no means to go to court", he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see about that".
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait", he thinks.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not even cover the amounts needed to maintain the community fund", recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the RPG Byty company, who adds that the neglected state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments with rent, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.200 million.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data highlighted in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties".
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per month per square meter", the screen says.
Just increased by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter", indicates RPG.
At 2,600 floors, rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not affect rents all at once, but will be scaled up over four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see graph) back into the flats, mainly in savings on heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rent increase agreement.
The architects have understood that the offices also need daycare.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would think that it also contains a small nursery with all the features of such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can visit it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose studio produced numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-garage.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of reduced working hours, the daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its workers as part of its social programme.
Builders and architects thus have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-nursery was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-garden is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
The financing granted (more than CZK 2.8 million) enabled them to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-nursery running with its own funds for three years.
The project was prepared over a year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the financing application.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, and a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are available round the clock.The nursery currently accommodates children of no age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
As it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can accommodate only a maximum of five children at a time, although more children attend during the day as the shifts increase.
The operation of the day care centre is flexible to suit the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the day care centre, irrespective of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten programme are comparable to the programme of the regular preschool.
The children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, including English.
The classroom has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can visit their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up the children late from school when away from work.
This way, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
Arch.Design is thus among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this programme reinforced staff marketing.
The House of Bones is still fascinating after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs look like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, striking colors, the novel use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and the omnipresent smoothly curved lines, all are typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The house's cover plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and wildlife.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way as to enhance the brightness of the colors.
The serpentine and twisted forms continue to amaze us even inside.
Wavy wood imitates window frames, railings, doorway ornaments, gazebos, and signs.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample neighbourhood at number 43 of the lively Passeig de Grácia shopping street, was born from the remodeling of a house built in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated on the design.
In fact, in his project plans emerged ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
Other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell Park of Gaudí, in which other pieces of it are located.
Because of its organic shape, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began calling it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the time with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may seem strange to have a forty-five degree inclination.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the building codes of the time and did not let himself be influenced by them.
Nevertheless, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself settled down on the lower floors.
The second floor had the living room and the third floor had the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without any problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, the white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The two-color game brings maximum light to all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the Unesco World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most charged of the publicly accessible apartments.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
The visits confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very profitable business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, reaching 16,50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry for other Gaudí constructions in the city.
