How to choose a mattress and a pillowcase: women and men look for different things
Not a pompous bed frame; what really gives a good bed its quality is the surface on which to lie down, that is, the mattress and the pillow.
First of all, they must be perfectly complementary so that they are adapted to the specific users.
Numerous factors come into play during the selection process, including the weight, height, health status and sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and the shroud are located is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cottage that is not usually heated, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat up" more slowly.
In addition, they are usually considerably heavier than standard polyurethane mattresses.
It is therefore necessary to turn them over more frequently.
If the central channels are not properly ventilated and are on a firm base above, they keep moisture in, and mold may even appear underneath.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft coating and will have trouble feeling comfortable on a lower, harder surface.
"Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep as well here".
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic".
"This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who have nervous system problems, so they receive bad information from the joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, as well as other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico".
You don't have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelasticity.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to its body heat.
Nothing puts pressure on you; at night, you won't be spinning like after a hard game.
He just sleeps better.
Viscoelastic also acts as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of its feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman who is about 180 cm tall will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, 180 cm in total.
In the case of single rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So a possible visit would also be comfortable.
"If not, a simple rule for calculating the width can be applied: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk to your elbows", advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert at Cechu čalouníků a dekoratérů, who has been working for many years on the subject of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture, a subject she teaches in specialized schools.
In double rooms, each needs its own bed and mattress, so during the purchase care must be taken to match the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, the beds will need to be mounted at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, models with springs inside at least 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
"When touching it with your hand or when sitting on the mattress, you should definitely not notice the springs", warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of shade.
Fully padded bedrooms, where the mattress and base are like Siamese, don't make sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and cannot be washed, which is often the case today.
And since we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat each night, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, experts reject slogans that talk of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
So the sellers advise: For mattresses that are 120 or 140 centimeters wide, take care to clean and wash the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be removed and easily washed.
Although mattress covers are now made with zippered closures all around, opening them into two parts (very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), handling them on larger models (and by one person) when lifting the mattress may seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a somier, do you have a firm board?
I never will!
So much for beds made for overnight guests.
However, you must make (if you do not already have) ventilation holes in the board and it must be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft coating.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-jointed sheet-mattresses containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut fibre) may be used, although it is always preferable to use a sheet-mattresses with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar region are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated.
The jointed sheet-mattress should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
This is a special fixture of the blades that allows the blades to be pressed or even tilted so that they "circle" the shoulders perfectly during sleep.
For men with very wide shoulders, this is something very important.
Even mattress manufacturers remember them, and in the "male" category, they began to use a softer area around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are cross- or panel-shaped cushions with the so-called multitorsion cushioning.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the voltage is lowered.
You should also bear in mind that even if you use the right mattress and pillow, if you use a bad pillow (large and "moulded"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can relax.
The recommended appropriate size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder-reinforced pillow or the softer area of the mattress) as the shoulder height.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers are still increasingly using natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, organic mattresses are in fashion.
The petroleum-based raw materials used to make polyurethane foam are filled with natural oils, such as castor oil or soybean oil.
In fact, practically all known manufacturers use soy.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the centre is made exclusively of natural materials", explains Petr Vašíček of the company Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the manufacture of mattress linings, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh forest or lavender aroma.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "cool" themselves with vegetable extracts from breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "warm" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel warmer.
The current favourites?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offers more permeability.
The combination of various cold foam and viscoelastic rigidities makes it possible to make mattresses of different areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you from seven thousand crowns upwards.
Those with a therapeutic function are usually subject to a lower VAT rate, since they are considered as healthcare.
The first to obtain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It's hard to save on mattresses and bed linens.
Sometimes the offers of manufacturers or sellers can be approved, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 kroner.
The second one is free.
The era of viscoelasticity with an open cell structure and high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
It was originally developed as a NASA material, because during takeoffs astronauts were subjected to enormous overload.
Tempur softened with heat and hardened with cold.
Thus, the human body, when warm, exerts a perfect effect and adapts its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal for preventing wounds, but also for improving sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foam is used not only in mattresses but also in sanitary products, for example, pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
The national manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver and the like.
More and more parents are using people-tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear for children is leading more and more people to think about GPS monitoring.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and contribute to cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it will be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were scared by the case of the missing Anička and began to inform about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that it is not spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I recognize that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases".
"Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons", adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bochková warns that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even young children are very creative about intentionally losing things if they want to avoid being controlled".
"Before, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device", says Bočková.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a premeditated kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check to see if the child is carrying any electronic device that can reveal his location".
"Now it's the phone".
"As the use of tracking devices spreads, you will also look for them, as their sale will undoubtedly be highly advertised".
"In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, their presence can help.
'The device can be configured to regularly transmit the position after a certain period.'
"If it is damaged, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question".
"The most expensive devices have a tiltmeter built in, so if the person simply slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question", Čech says.
In its view, such a service can be obtained even with mobile smartphones with navigation, which only need to be equipped with special software.
The problem with the current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
So you can get lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for that reason tests are currently being carried out with devices that resemble a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added benefit that a potential assailant may not identify the device".
"Or to identify it after a certain time, which can save the police time", he adds.
Although the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology as used for vehicle tracking.
This is the verification of position with a GPS system (used in normal car navigation) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough machetes to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to ignite explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defence added 224 kilometres of wick to its arsenal.
So, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosives wick from STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mecha by saying that the soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of mecha per year.
According to the calculations of the army's pyrotechnics, with whom MF DNES was in contact, it is decided, however, that, in such a case, they should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high-command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want exemptions either, Minister of Defence Alexander Vondr and Army Captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could the army be justified in spending sixty kilometres of machete.
That length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough supplies for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally to Minister Vondra recently because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even shooting practices are limited for money.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also cannot understand why we are repeatedly bought such quantities of mecha".
"But it's your choice, and you will no doubt know why you act this way".
"For us, the military is a good customer, and as a company we try to satisfy them", admits Jan Děcký, commercial director of STV Group.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of mecha saying he will also have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of STV Group points out that the wick has a useful life of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four", says one soldier who, because of possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each round must be carefully checked to see if it is still reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument from the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of mecha, he got a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers", said Pejšek, spokesman for the Defense Ministry's procurement center.
Just to compare: the annual consumption of wick by the police pyrotechnics, who dispose of the ammunition of the Second World War or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
Furthermore, the police always ask for just the right amount to run out of ammunition before it is out of stock.
They decided to do so for safety reasons for the pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The Ministry is already having difficulty finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the Czechoslovak army of 200,000 was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometres of old mecha will have to be removed, which is now being bought "cheaply".
I still live off the contacts I made through the contest.
The fact that he won the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest helped Lukáš Pytloun in the sale of his hotel franchises.
The last edition, the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest was won by 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec.
His success story seems to be taken from a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun loved to travel.
While abroad, he realized that there was a need for quality accommodation at a good price in Liberec.
With the savings he had accumulated from seasonal jobs abroad and a bank loan, he bought a half-destroyed five-story house.
Considering that he was still in his third year of college, he was really brave.
"The value of accommodation in our area has now made me want to do something about it", says Lukáš Pytloun.
He started renting the first floor to foreign workers.
All the income he earned he reinvested in the building, which gradually became a 54-room boarding house.
Since then, in seven years in business, he gradually managed to open in Liberec four guesthouses, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of around 300 in all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year he opened another of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov or Tisé, to which we sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise", said the number one entrepreneur last year.
"This sale of hotel opening licences was helped in no small part by the fact that we won the 'Entrepreneur of the Year' competition", Pytloun adds gratefully.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, they still congratulated me often and, I must say, it was very nice", he recalls.
He certainly recommends anyone who wants to try out any of the companies that are in the competition.
But he believes that it is not necessary to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He claims that, until now, he continues to live off contacts and acquaintances that, without the contest, he might not have obtained.
"I've started to collaborate regularly with some people I met through the contest".
The fame associated with success, in his opinion, also included in the employees,
In total, there are about 70.
"I've seen them show greater loyalty and are proud to be part of something that has gained general recognition".
"It is not, by any means, my own personal success, but it is the result of the hard work of the whole team".
"Only my name appears on the front page", says Lukáš Pytloun modestly today.
I wish my successor a calmer year than we've had at Farmet.
The euphoria for victory was soon dissipated by the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the hard work of the winner, Farmet may have already been through the worst.
The owner of the Farmet company, Karel Žďárský, won first prize in the last edition of Vodafone's "Company of the Year" contest, last year at the "Slavic House" in Prague.
The jury appreciated his efforts, which enabled him to turn a small technical workshop in Česká Skalice into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
"I can say that the award encouraged not only me but all my collaborators and improved our confidence to fight the competition", says last year's winner.
The history of Farmet began with the desire to make something useful.
So when the state offered Karel Žďárský's father the rental of a small workshop as compensation for the seizure of property during communism, he did not hesitate too much; he resigned his position in the company where he worked and, with a couple of colleagues, founded the company with his father of plastic batteries.
Soon after, they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
Eight years later they became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in central Europe.
They also gained a greater presence among the non-specialist public after achieving success in the media competition.
"Not only did our customers start to see the Farmet brand as considerably better, but foreign partners also started to value working with a company that had more success in their country", says Karel Žďárský.
