A survey that reveals ridiculous standards
The Absurdity of the Year poll is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
He's already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity survey of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was adopted by more than a third of the nearly four thousand voters.
For example, the social security administration would ask for an extract from the trade register, although its officials can get it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the poll, that's changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the commercial register when it checks the taxation of the insured", declared ČSSZ spokeswoman Jana Buraňová.
The aim of the "Absurdity of the Year" survey is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year, for the fourth time, it is part of the business competition of the Hospodářské noviny publication and is also starting to attract interest among the general public.
While last year's edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it has practically reached four thousand.
And this is not surprising, since we still have several extra legal obligations that must be respected simply to trade.
"We are perhaps the world's number one in terms of paperwork required for tax returns", says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, the simplification of business rules has been a stated objective of all governments.
However, compared with the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranks 74th in terms of conditions for business, eight places lower than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was first held in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can point to some administrative or bureaucratic nonsense every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. The organiser of the competition then selects seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The nonsense that gets the most votes wins.
For this year's survey, more than 100 were submitted, including 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for road and motorway maintenance pay tolls or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of 70 proposals for this year is published on the competition pages.
The announcement of the contest, which is always held in early November at Prague's Wenceslas Square, is part of an event in which political and social figures usually participate.
This year, for example, the event was attended by Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
"Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the State continuously impedes entrepreneurs, so my aim is to eliminate every year at least 30 paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade", announced Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not put on hold.
In 2007, what most disturbed people was the obligation of the entrepreneur to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, the intention to go with a post to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was abolished in the new industrial law.
The obligation that finished second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. the notification to the employment office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
And the third one wins.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales in their office.
So this year the Ministry of Health issued a statement saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
