Families will have to pay extra expenses of several hundred crowns a month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
Consequently, families will have to withdraw several hundred crowns more per month from the portfolio from January than they do now.
The price of electricity rises by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for water supply and many cities are also raising the price of central heating.
The electricity bill for families living in apartments should be about 100 crowns more per year than it is now.
However, the main electricity suppliers reduced prices, as support for renewable energy production, in particular photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas is moderately expensive, especially at the time when heating is used most and therefore consumption is higher.
In this case, they must also count on a couple of hundred crowns more a year.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive throughout the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is planned mainly by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about 50 crowns more per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 crowns more per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rent for infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, the Prague residents will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
Rental prices for 450,000 rented flats in Prague, where regulation will end in January, may rise considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take those who disagree with the new rent to court.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could increase next year by up to 10%.
The young Czechs get drunk on Fernet and rum.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
Those are the drinks that provoke those who end up in medical care young drinkers under the age of fifteen.
Children who end up lying in hospital continuously to overcome hangovers are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is out of fashion, because it takes a long time to get drunk".
"Now the trend is for strong alcoholic beverages", says Luděk Pelikán, head of pediatrics at the Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they get a bottle from their father's cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka".
"Wodka has the advantage of being lighter with juice and less odorful", he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman for Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Usually it's Fernet or rum".
"That's modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren".
"In some cases, they use homemade water", adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, it's thirteen and fourteen-year-old drinkers who usually show up in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where she has been working since this year, she worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to go in maybe four times".
"It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, plus a mixture of ecstasy", says the department doctor about this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party".
"The interesting thing is that her mother was not surprised that her daughter disappeared for 48 hours", the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest by parents or even their clear tolerance of drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among youths.
Experts point out that in the case of children, dependency is not a word.
"An alcoholic is a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children".
"In those who drink repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment", explains chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year in the pediatric clinic of Motol forty drunken children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come with severe intoxication and must stay in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after an out-of-state medical examination, go home to their parents or the police, are not counted.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink a drink, there are three seasonal highs and lows for Pelikán to mention: witches' day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such circumstances, they drink to the bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays".
"On Halloween, I've seen as many as seven drunken children at the same time", Pelikán adds.
Drunkards who spend the night in detox under medical supervision, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headaches, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, are avoided by injecting a serum with glucose and nutrients that the body lacks.
"These people are much better off because after a hectic night, they get up well and don't feel any pain".
"They just get confused about where they are", Pelikán notes, adding that patients often lose their sense of humor at least when they see the expenses they have incurred.
The transfer by ambulance and the hospitalization in a room for serious patients costs about ten thousand crowns.
"I have often used cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job so that you would earn enough to pay yourself that night", Pelikán adds.
The medical insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for treatment costs, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159s found in foreign hands for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, with which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa - EADS is located.
This is the first time that a device of this type has been in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
At the time, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
It is the L-159T1 two-seat version, which was previously used by the Czech Army and was still in flying condition.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat L-159.
These are still held at Aer Vodochody and the intermediary of the sale, the company Omnipol, took over them last week.
Jan Peješk, from the defense press department, indicates that it is not yet known when the planes will be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
"The L-159 monoplane, on the other hand, was separated from the aircraft repaired long ago, without any investments or additional contributions from the Ministry".
"The two-seater L-159T1s were exchanged in their current state", he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army is not without two-seaters, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for an amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seaters.
One of the new planes has already been delivered to the army in July, the other will be delivered at the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS committed to adding the aircraft to the equipment of some allied countries.
'The contract clearly states that the company EADS is the one to take the L-159s out and that they will be used for pilot training from NATO countries.'
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how they will be used in this context", Pejšek points out.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published early on that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for one Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.500 million crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense management claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 overseas.
The Czech army has acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already brought the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by conducting a European tender and not by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last one should arrive at Prague's Kbely airport in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have a longer index than the ring are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer magazine.
It could depend on your testosterone level, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger may be a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to 60 years of age", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could therefore help determine which men should be screened for prostate cancer, particularly if this trait is associated with genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, Eeles said.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to get prostate cancer as the 19 percent of those with the same length of fingers.
In men with an index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; in men aged less than 60%, the reduction was 87%.
The relationship between the lengths of the two fingers in question, as determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he is aware of the study, but that he does not think the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "completely demonstrated".
