Grammy nominations: jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is the surprise pick in the category of breakthrough artist.
Act on the request of a president and people will probably notice you.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old bassist and jazz singer personally selected by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, was one of the surprises at this year's Grammys with a high-profile nomination in the category of Best New Artist.
Considering that Spalding has been an acclaimed jazz figure since her 2008 album, "Hope", the nomination is thought-provoking, but it respects the Grammys' rules that an artist must have released no more than three albums before recording the one that "determines the public identity of that artist".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", was undoubtedly a breakthrough and, considering her light and pleasant vocal style, as well as a great skill with influences from pop, funk and Latin rhythms, one can at least draw a distinction between Spalding and the road to Norah Jones' 2003 success, the closest equivalent to the Grammys voters, who lately have concentrated on the jazz realm for this category.
In the remaining categories, Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity", a thrilling and magnificent record that was one of last year's favorites.
Among Iyer's competitors are veteran saxophonist James Moody with "Moody 4B" and keyboardist John Beasley for "Positootly".
Shorty's trombone, a New Orleans favorite and a regular guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the contemporary jazz category, which otherwise leans considerably toward fusion as in albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
The wild punk of Darcy James Argue's Secret Society earned a well-deserved recognition in the big band category, competing against the great chamber jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and the ever-risky Dave Holland, whose live album with his octet, "Pathways", was a great example of the bassist's democratic leadership in his band.
Nominations for the Grammy Awards: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey for best direction of classical albums
The classical music nominees for the 53rd Grammy Awards include a mix of musicians and composers from around the world.
The top nominations were for Michael Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", for piano and orchestra, in five movements, and Steve Mackey for "Dreamhouse", an eclectic three-movement orchestral work.
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a piece commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
The classical music nominations are distributed in thirteen categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo albums.
The category for classic producer of the year includes five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin, and James Mallinson.
The nominees for the classical music album are Bruckner for Symphonies No. 3 and No. 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey for "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" by various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg for "Lulu" by the Royal Opera House orchestra; Adolf Hasse for "Marc Antonio and Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho for "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the Mariinsky Theatre orchestra and choir; and Arthur Sullivan for "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Composers nominated for a Grammy for contemporary compositions include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionately Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a session recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The piece, about 30 minutes long, is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" is nominated for instrumental solo performance with orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin player Avi Avital, who performed the concert with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"He composed it with sounds from the Middle East and numerous scales and rhythms from North Africa", Dorman stated in a telephone interview.
85-year-old conductor Pierre Boulez was nominated in the orchestral performance category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra during a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Among the instrumental soloists nominated are pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
The nominees for vocal soloists this year are all women: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mixing category, soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots - My Life, My Song".
