An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it proves that it is possible for life forms to exist without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That makes it very peculiar, though it is a short distance from being a truly 'alien' life-form", commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in the Thursday online edition of Science.
For a long time, it has been thought that there are six major elements essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the find is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the holding of a press conference to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated much speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "does show is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to drive their biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements we consider essential for life may not be so fixed", commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure", added Cockell.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could substitute one for the other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate between them".
"However, arsenic is different enough that it does not work as well as phosphorus, so it enters and, so to speak, disrupts the biochemical machinery", explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they adapted to and used to grow.
The microbe grows best on phosphorus, but the fact that it can live on arsenic instead raises the possibility that there could be a form of life that naturally uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but no example has ever been found to prove that it works.
Arsenic was more common in the earliest ages of the Earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
"It does suggest that there may be other ways of generating life, not just the way life formed on Earth in ancient times", said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
