The lion is ready to roar again as the restructuring of MGM gets final court approval.
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, MGM has finally gotten the green light to start over.
On Thursday, a New York federal bankruptcy judge officially approved the creditors' "pre-arranged" plan to write off roughly $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and premiering movies and television shows.
Thursday's ruling confirms that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal obstacles to MGM being relaunched under Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a smaller studio.
The staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320 members.
In fact, MGM will not exit Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a planned $500 million credit facility to finance the operations and productions of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the credit, which it is contributing with $75 million, and is expected to be financed by mid-December.
The restructuring process of the firm began in May 2009, when the investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to advise on the management needed to manage its finances, while struggling to make interest payments of $300 million per year.
In August, Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron Chairman and bankruptcy recovery expert, known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial woes and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors required much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed to put the company up for sale at the end of 2009.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than $2 billion that creditors were seeking.
By the spring of this year, he was back on the design table as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of debate and internal disagreements, was finally backed by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially comes out of bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper's companies will receive multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have been collecting $375,000 a month for their company management services, will receive a "success fee" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which released only one film this year, and put together an annual slate of seven or eight films to be released in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to arrange a separate loan of between $265 and $275 million to finance its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns approximately 18% of MGM's debt, had been trying to arrange a studio merger with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent talks between the two companies did not result in an agreement.
Tech Toys wants to keep their gift budget balanced
While the iPad is the leading candidate to be this year's most wonderful toy, followed perhaps by the Microsoft Kinect video game system, both can mean a significant bump in your gift budget.
Consider that for the price of an iPad you can buy five BMX bikes for $99 each, and a Kinect set costs the same as 10 classic beaded jump ropes, or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
I recently visited three national toy retailers, Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us, and BJ's Wholesale Club, to see which electronic toys I could buy for less than $80.
It was immediately clear that Moore's Law has been working; this year's tech toy will probably have more power, cost the same and even a little less compared to last year's.
Also, while there are generally fewer new toys with associated websites, two of the best known of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offerings.
And button-battery-powered toys are on the rise, as are toys with rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us, unless otherwise noted.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for 3 and older) are stuffed toys the size of a guinea pig that sing a note when their bellies are squeezed.
One squeeze equals one note, and a second squeeze starts to put together a song.
If you buy more than one, they'll sing in harmony.
Warning: Once you start squeezing, you can't stop.
For singing combined with dancing, Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price, $60, for 2 years and older) is the best option.
Borrowing technology from last year's Elmo Live, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays shift-shift games like Simon Dice, and can make the moon-step, thanks to its innovative articulated feet with locking wheels.
The children who tried the toy used Mickey as a dance instructor, although their parents complained about the lack of volume control.
If you're a kid in the '80s, you might remember Alphie, one of the first computer-based educational toys.
He's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for 3 years and up), with a backpack full of question cards designed to turn a car ride into a session with an occasional self-correcting exercise book.
If you are hesitant to give your child his or her smartphone, here are three independent alternatives.
VTech's MobiGo ($60, 3-8 years) is the cheapest and easiest to use, featuring a qwerty keyboard; although games don't teach as effectively as the Leapster Explorer ($70, 3-12 years), it is the first major upgrade of the Leapster line, with a newer, brighter screen.
None of the versions are compatible with the old cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90, 3-7 years old) uses an iTunes-like system to present games and e-books, and has an SD card slot that allows viewing family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash (30 dollars, Hasbro, for 8 and up) is a game of five blocks barely larger than a matchbox, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to put words together by placing the blocks in a row before time runs out; it's formidable for an impromptu word-making competition.
More and more toys have some kind of online connection.
Based on their presence in toy stores alone, the two biggest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
To buy your child a pet online at Club Penguin, for example, you can get a Disney Club Penguin 2" Mix 'N Match Figure Pack, ($5, 6 to 12 years old) that includes a coin with a hidden code.
When you change the code online, your child gets enough credits at the Club Penguin store for two items.
These could include roller skates on wheels or a Puffle pet toy.
Slightly larger than the pig in your toothbrush, the Hexbug Nano ($10, for 5 years and up) is the latest in a line of microrobots powered by button batteries.
The fake insect moves rapidly on 12 vibrating silicone legs, in random directions.
It's fun to make a maze of blocks to see if you can find the way out.
It's also durable.
Ours was able to leave the kitchen table and even spend some time inside our dog's mouth.
A more moderate side of law enforcement is promoted in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the way in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, the body-sized urban police of China, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and inclination to violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of onlookers.
"Signed!"
"Whoa, whoa, whoa!"
Show them, he whispered, "how pretty the girls are!"
Four girls who barely made it through their teenage years wearing white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed over the hair tied with blue and white striped studs.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance", said Mr. Tang, scornfully.
"The models are cute".
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China's urban inspectors.
A city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
Guangdong Province changed the greyish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, 50 officers reportedly surrounded a rambling snack cart, and watched it with a constant frown for half an hour, until the street vendor packed his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical image change.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough police a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's meager respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are authorized only to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat to death a passerby after he used his cell phone to film them dissolving a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted online, describing how to effectively whip criminals without bleeding them.
This year, a Shanghai street vendor of watermelons suffered brain damage after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government", lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really thorough cleanup".
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district notified eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether the women had real duties or were simply a stage diversion.
The answer seems to be a little of both.
The district notice called for female candidates ages 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features".
They must have been above average height, over five feet, two and a half inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is compulsory.
Officials said the work was too physically demanding for women over 25.
"Your image is the important thing", an unnamed district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc".
Next comes the temperament "and the inner qualities".
Female chengguan are like florists, he said, adding, "besides being florists, they will have other responsibilities".
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city administration office, is not eager to back up that description.
But he noted that height requirements were standard in many Chinese job advertisements for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
If this means being handsome, it's a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the handicapped or disfigured should not be presented.
"We can't allow a lame person or a humpback to come to work here", Mr. Zheng said.
"Your image would not be good".
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with his cheeks red and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn't think the accent on her looks is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" he asked with a sardonic look.
His fellow dusty worker, 21-year-old Xu Yang, said, "Our work should present the image of the city".
They also do not object to their work being on time, they said, because they harbor greater career ambitions than simply scaring off vendors in the alleys where they are supposed to circumscribe their business.
Each morning, the squad faces about a dozen street vendors who hurl themselves on foot or by bicycle, trying to sell as many tofu buns or bowls as possible before being thrown out.
"Mr. Wang, you have to leave".
"We've told you so many times!" said Ms. Xu as a salesman fled on foot, temporarily abandoning his bicycle-drawn cart with noodle liners.
Officers describe their duties as more monotonous than exhausting.
"It's pretty much the same every day", said Huang Jing, 20, who studies marketing in his spare time.
"Very routine".
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate merchandise from vendors.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
