The prosecution will not press charges against Senator Ensign.
The senator's lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have exonerated Senator John Ensign of criminal charges stemming from his affair with a former campaign aide and his efforts to lobby for work for the woman's husband.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said it felt "surely pleased" with the decision, which came after a year-long investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of their investigation and that they have no plans to charge him in this matter".
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign may have conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
The interviews, email and other documents first leaked in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, obtain lucrative lobbying work, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton work and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign aide, he was barred by law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for one year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former government employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute", said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients under investigation by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics attorneys said the department appeared cautious about accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens amid procedural misconduct charges.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards", said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws don't apply to them", he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law".
Coggins refused to elaborate on the legal arguments he gave to the prosecutors.
"I don't feel comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to reverse an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said they didn't have enough evidence to prove the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, which got a job through lobbying thanks to the help Ensign gave Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him he was "squatting" the Interior Ministry over a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and called the transportation secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When news of the affair first emerged last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, she said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department's lead and conclude its investigation.
"Senator Ensign wishes to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada", he said.
