In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely-watched trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a Cheshire, Connecticut family, is set to come to an official end, with the judge's imposition of the jury-voted death penalty.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have filed court papers outlining the arguments in appeals that are likely to occupy the courts for years to come.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reporting on the process, including extensive use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created "a circus atmosphere", and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details made public passions exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appellate judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
