For decades, appellate courts have recognized that coverage of high-profile cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in its decision, in the case of Sheppard v. Maxwell, that there was "a carnival atmosphere in the process" due to the media.
The crime is believed to have been inspired by the TV show and movie "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said that the appellate courts that reviewed Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later might be intrigued by the argument that new rules might be needed to control the way communication from courtrooms, something unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
