Some jurors have said they were horrified by the photographs of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury who had criticized prosecutors, and that he incorrectly pressed for a verdict for his bizarre decision to order the jury to deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But his arguments about the effect of intense coverage of the trial may attract most of the interest.
They noted in a denial of the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media was continually adding fuel to the fire of emotion about the case.
"The daily swarm of tweets from the media, cameras and reporters outside the courthouse", the lawyers wrote, "was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps in the entire state".
His attention to Twitter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that immediate news was more important than slower-delivered reports was a Luddite view that would make the court's policy on controlling coverage weak in future proceedings.
But some lawyers said that appellate courts were often attracted by arguments about the adjustment required in courts because of social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In their letter, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, overturning Dr. Sheppard's conviction because of the coverage of the trial, and made it clear that they would demand that new media require new rules.
"This case", they wrote, "represents the Sheppard v. Maxwell case of the 21st century".
Can civility bridge the divides?
After a remarkable campaign of invective and negativity, a little civility has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of future genuine bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the big issues that must be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion of the two parties' differences, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to gain partisan points.
The public meeting of the President's deficit committee on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates the members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a testing period, probing each other for signs of cooperativism and compromise, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenditure, health care or welfare, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no question that things have changed with respect to the way things are said", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then die out.
That's good".
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda for the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and nobody's in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make it seem that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is increased optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues in the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things that must be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation", he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they should try to deliver on their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health care law.
These party lines are already clearly visible in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reform of the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own estimation, have forcibly introduced the deficit issue into the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been struggling to get close to that number.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected to the panel, suggesting that on tax issues there is, at least at present, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama over the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch closely the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as merely the prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked US document portrays Moscow as a haven for corruption
The city is controlled by a "kleptocracy", which leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects directly to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service operate huge blackmail schemes, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of the bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called "vertical authority", takes its share as money rises in the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and he blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there's been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several libel suits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested he was corrupt, he stated: "It's crazy, it's a hoax, it's a nuisance".
According to polls, Russians overwhelmingly believe their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for diplomats of a foreign country to do that.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government with crime have led some to call it 'dysfunctional,' and to claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government", the note states.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a criminal and mafia term that literally means 'roof' or protection) that runs through the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all sectors of the bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in the Moscow criminal world".
"Luzhkov is at the top".
"The SFS, MVD and the militia are on the second level".
"Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level".
"This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a vacuum in some areas, because the city does not provide some services".
The report claims that the SFS collects money from the biggest companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report stated, "explained that Moscow business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (instead of organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law".
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority".
The note notes that while the money collection is complete, the protection can be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly find their business closed under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has admitted that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on bureaucrats", said Georgy Satarov, director of the Moscow-based Indem think tank, in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy".
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia".
Without politics, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the nongovernmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked from least to most corrupt).
The disclosure of the US embassy note, which didn't happen until late at night Moscow time, is sure to cause disgust within the Russian government, and while Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that the WikiLeaks documents might be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation that claimed American diplomats were calling him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policies in this country", he said.
"But to be honest with you, we didn't suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way".
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School remembered the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader and cared about his people", said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, the long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront those who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodian court issued the first conviction for a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can do nothing", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil".
"This is creating divisions within families".
During the Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurgency that lasted until the last movement surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating in the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the Raza soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gotten little benefit after the surrender", said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have embedded the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime".
"They were raised with no concept of doing business".
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before turning to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine", he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone".
"But now life is hard because we have to provide for ourselves".
The current Khmer Rouge tribunal has also caused concern here.
Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the main leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases beyond those four.
This didn't do much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge government in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are thought to have died.
On a recent embarrassing afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden poles on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She claimed that if the court summoned her she would not appear.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable", he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court prosecutes more suspects, although experts and historians question this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to the Khmer, is to put the broken pieces back together", he said.
"It is our duty to gather these broken pieces together so that we can understand".
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", 75 pages long.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's secondary school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But her parents reacted with skepticism when she took the book home for study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court", he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are starting to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too much weed and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black soot covered by a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cellphone salesman, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him", he said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot's last rest, where he would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of good luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its weapons-grade uranium stockpile
In a surprise victory for President Obama's campaign to protect nuclear material around the world, the government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it will give up its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the sidelines of a security summit.
For years, the US government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and it seemed they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that a couple of classified operations were conducted with Belarus in the last two months, to remove 84.82 kg of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This set the stage for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material, approximately 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke on condition of anonymity due to the confidentiality of the matter.
The agreement appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit".
"This shows that this process is working", said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said the agreement is "a very significant and important step" by Belarus.
In April 2009 Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide over the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be seventh.
A dozen countries did it under the George W. Bush administration.
At the time of the Obama Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have kept the highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of which is basically weapons-grade uranium) and the low-enriched uranium", Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell them to anyone".
"We use it for research purposes, that's all".
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said the first task of removing uranium from Belarus in October was particularly difficult, as the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded onto a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to officials, the second operation was completed on Monday and was done by plane.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on the tasks, and most of the money was used to supply Belarus with the low-enriched uranium research facility, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an official at the Department of Energy who works on Global Threat Reduction, said that "this was coordinated and orchestrated very carefully to strengthen the trust" that led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
The James Martin Center for Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will seek to eliminate its reserve by 2012, according to the joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to Lukashenko's harsh crackdown on human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggested a potential detente.
It was stated that "while welcoming progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains a central issue for improving bilateral relations, and is essential for the progress of the country and its citizens".
