Sport and law-breaking
Tricks like Alonso and Ramos's against Ajax show ingenuity but no will to escape a penalty.
The allegedly orchestrated expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has prompted rivers of ink to be written about whether such behaviour is or is not anti-sports and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes to go before the game was over (which their team had clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when they made three fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will finish as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction in the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can pass to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather a common practice in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten, but followed, rules of this sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that it has been played by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which in past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any event, the debate is on whether such behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulation, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether such behaviour constitutes a breach of the law, since it is in fact an act which respects the sporting rules but seems to evade their purpose.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they do to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets of the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these goods referred to by fair play is to prevent the team of offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not comply with what we normally call cheating or fraud, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious so as to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the punishment.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the intentional misconduct examined.
It seems necessary to note here that neither the rival is placed at a disadvantage nor the same game is profitable, for the result of the action is obviously to leave the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team may be eliminated at the first replacement, and also with this performance the players complete a penalty match and move to the second round of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, going round and round, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which is to take strategic decisions that make the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law-fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping punishment or running from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and law-breaking is blurred, I think this was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, stems from two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the directive was transmitted.
The damage to sporting principles caused by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
