Pakistan's nuclear program is causing great concern in the US
Islamabad is producing atomic weapons "at a faster rate than any other country".
WikiLeaks leaks confirm the ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns that are being raised in Washington over the Pakistani nuclear program.
Apart from the enlightening and juicy details they offer about the content of the talks and the thoughts of the accredited American diplomatic representatives in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries on nuclear security, instead of increasing, is "growing", and that the unstable Asian country is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but remain stored by components to make it difficult to destroy them in case of attack - is one of the main reasons for the uncertainty in Washington.
So lists Ambassador Anne W. Patterson in Pakistan in a report prior to the visit of then-National Security Adviser James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersal of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of transportation of atomic materials".
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programmes is seen, not only by the United States but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to keep on guard.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the fall in educational and cultural standards, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people working in nuclear or missile programs", said Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev at a meeting with his American counterparts.
The most newsworthy of the leaked documentation by the Julian Assange portal is the declining cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and the high pace of Pakistani nuclear weapons production.
A May embassy dispatch, calling communication with Pakistan "frustrating", said: "Transparency is often lacking; offers of help go unanswered or are dismissed".
In another message, Peter Lavoy, a National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
Ambassador Patterson also asks Washington, during a visit by Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it "very clear" to the responsible that "the Pakistan Army must end its tacit support for terrorist groups".
