Interpol is issuing a red alert in order to track the movements and locate Assange wherever he is.
Everything about WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated maze where it's difficult to be certain about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a "red alert" to "locate and track the movements" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
It is not new, but dates from November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter million US diplomatic documents but with the sexual abuse allegations the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer for Wikileaks' creator, Mark Stephens, assures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr Assange".
It was on the 20th that the international police force based in Lyons (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
As it stands, the 188 countries of Interpol have indications to identify or locate Assange "with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, the organization has explained, do consider the so-called red notice a free way to proceed with an arrest - which must be undertaken by the national police force -, especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The movement has outraged Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing that the 39-year-old Wikileaks founder has shown himself willing to answer questions from the Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, who is compared to the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, head of Stalin's security.
"This looks like a hunt, not a legal persecution", the letter denounces.
While the world is searching for him - and his mother is defending her son's innocence from Australia - Assange remains unknown, but not silent.
On Monday, he granted an interview to the editor of Time magazine via Skype from an undetermined location, a conversation in which he asked for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering American diplomats to spy on the UN violating international treaties that the US has signed, he should resign", he said.
His opinion was denounced yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd".
