China maintains greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of that country at the COP16 assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that he supports his offer to reduce for 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its emission of greenhouse gases.
China is keeping its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to convert its industry.
In fact, he explained, in the past four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
He said China's climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including the approval last year of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set for reducing emissions of gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the federal authorities have been working in a coordinated manner with state and local authorities, to achieve the objectives of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, various multiannual plans, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, abound, are underway or have already been completed.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which has been implemented over the last five years and has received investment from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private sector.
A provincial project on climate change is also underway, another for the change of incandescent foci for savers and one more for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the government's scientific adviser on climate change, said China's efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he pointed out, China's per capita greenhouse gas emissions are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in the use of energy, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do the same by 2020, he said.
