US changes rules for visa
You must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centre before your interview at the Consular Section; the cost and the waiting time will be less.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for issuing visas at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) before their interview at the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, as there will be no need to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another payment for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant shall only make a lump sum payment covering all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa do not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but only to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Because the biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay in the Consular Section for less time than in the past.
Also, those who apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $ 26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
