The use of consortia of undertakings poses a serious ethical problem for the Québec Party, threatening to eliminate competition and raise prices.
"This is a new method of collusion and elimination of competition".
"That is, people, instead of doing it in secret, now do it openly", said Sylvain Simard, a member of the Quebec Party, at a press conference yesterday.
Earlier this morning Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, firmly denying that any collusion with this contract had occurred.
"I'm getting tired", he protested, defending that the PQ had acted "dishonestly" and "lacking rigor".
He pointed out that "at the very least" the PQ should apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice throughout the world.
It is usually a partnership with a time limit allowing two or more companies to pool their expertise to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project is highly complex, given the scale of the works.
The works have already started and will last until 2012.
In any event, the contract was awarded without any competition being involved; it was a negotiation.
Moreover, the consortium formula is no longer the exception to the rule in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir reported last week, the formula for consortia in the technical advisory sector is being investigated by the Government.
A quick look at the Quebec Commercial Register identifies more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
Dessau thus works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal person, namely Dessau.
With regard to the Énergie gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that 'the James Bay territory responds to a particular labour dynamic and Hydro-Québec has responded specifically to it since the 1970s'.
The head of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), gave an explanation which highlighted the fact that the project management contract was awarded directly.
"If you respond to a tender and there are few participants, your prices will be higher".
"You have two options: you can contact the players in the sector and say to them: we will negotiate a satisfactory agreement at a good price".
"The idea is that it is not the price that matters, but the competition of the people", Mr Laporte said.
The contract awarded to the Énergie gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts worth more than $50,000 won by the Quebec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following the verification, Le Devoir has identified 109 contracts for technical advice awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to undertakings or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has obtained 22 contracts, Génivar has obtained 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not taking into account its participation in Énergie gérance.
All the contracts were negotiated.
In total, they amount to 449,783,344 dollars, including the Énergie gérance contract of 295,131,564 dollars.
Sylvain Simard has suggested that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Liberal Party of Quebec".
Minister Normandeau has indicated that the PQ is also linked to these companies, which "finance" it, before specifying that it is rather their leaders.
