Another finding: half of consumers question the reliability of official certificates for products called fair, as well as the credibility of products and brands labeled as "eco-responsible", says the Barometer.
Similarly, only 14.6% of Quebecers take seriously the speeches of politicians on this issue.
In any event, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this sector of consumption, which currently supports about one third of Quebec consumers.
In fact, gaps and the dubious nature of the information mean that 46% of consumers reject this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, one third of Quebecers say they also distrust the supposed returns of the ecological products or services that are being sold to them.
Moreover, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, in particular, changed the brand of one or more products to respect their convictions.
61% have prioritized shopping in their neighbourhood stores and have preferred to buy food products grown in their region, notes the Barometer.
Greener and more responsible (the responsible consumption index has reached 64 points out of a high of 100 this year), the Homo consumus of Quebec loves to take the recycling king's place, trying to reduce its impact on the environment by caring for the protection of wildlife.
