A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that must be carried out to stabilize the planet's climate before 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of a series of major concrete projects which the UN hopes will be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still control between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluorescent light bulbs or, even better, by light-emitting diode (LED) bulbs, much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from the planet's car fleet.
At Copenhagen last year, the major emitter countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that would reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should be reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to avoid it being uncontrolled.
In incandescent bulbs, 95 percent of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5 percent, or light, is produced.
In the case of fluorescent light bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by a further twofold.
Fluorescent light bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives us an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be implemented in 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
On top, they contain no mercury.
Various specialists have expressed reservations about fluorescent light bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report says, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not fluorescent light bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity wasted by incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, such plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power stations, which would cost 2.5 billion to build.
