Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal which only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
It also predicts profound changes on an international scale and a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every dossier created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" US revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except Berlusconi's) and Gaddafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of publicly known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do new research (or do not know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those engaged in occultism do not just trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to the secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret service (if he could not be, I don't know, editor of Libération) is lazy (or has little eagerness), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they are merely saying what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the Second World War and since Heads of State can make phone calls or catch a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into centres of espionage.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly well, we just pretend we don't know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly is a breach of duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image to American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could access the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both the victims and the 'doers'.
But let's get into the true nature of what happened.
In the old days, in Orwell's time, you could think of yourself as a big brother who controlled every move of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every move thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, every hotel visited, every highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as is happening now, that even the crypts of power's secrets cannot escape a hacker's control, the relationship of control ceases to be one-way and becomes circular again.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be held back if it can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without any secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all her power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on such a powerful power?
It is clear that in the future the Member States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the net, as it would be like putting it on a street sign.
But it is also evident that, with today's technology, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the telephone.
Nothing is easier than discovering whether and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of his counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, at the moment, my prediction is science fiction and therefore novel, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been memorized or, at best, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I've written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, which is to say, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph.
Video tapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, going forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now CDs (digital) only allow to go forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, in enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, whereas by plane, with the travel it entails, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication techniques to bring us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the embassies in secret.
Today, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's financial promises are lacking
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (called fast start) made by developed countries have been met.
And the French bags have been uncovered.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures taken by its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was a good result and was appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be 'new and additional' to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, it does not refer to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) as long as it aims to respect its commitment to 'new and additional' funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution of grants and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the calculation method.
Some, such as France, consider that each euro lent is equal to one euro donated.
Of course, it is difficult to justify such an effort: it is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments which are profitable (often projects related to reducing emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is false to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan to the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find this useful: it "meets" its 420 million euro commitment by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, whereas the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, France is abusing its fast start financing in two ways: first, in relation to actions in time and, second, in relation to the actual financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, it gives the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional" as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has taken care of the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not stupid...
The early financing chapter is a small detail, relatively short-term, in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope not.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of meeting its commitments and in the same way as the other EU countries.
But France in particular could move the debate on the stakes in longterm financing forward (another essential chapter currently being discussed): we will not get rid of the question of the 'additional nature' or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have hope for the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its view on the 'additional nature' and use of the loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning on pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study released Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problematic treatment", purchased in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food that is usually consumed by a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruit and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day), as well as the sweets, were tested in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Although in virtually all cases the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that the exposure of consumers to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE pollutants is of concern", the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can damage the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil and intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even bread or gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the tests revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon stew was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk posed by these "pollutant cocktails" to the consumer "is probably underestimated", says the study.
The European Ecology-Green Alliance (EE-LV) has proposed, "in view of the gravity of the situation", a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
